[2.6 The Relational Algebra]
    - consists of a set of operations that take one or two relations as input and produce a new relation as their result.

    - "unary" operations: select, project, and rename operations
        -> because they operate on one relation.

    - "binary" operations: union, Cartesian product, and set difference
        -> operate on pairs of relations.

    (2.6.1 The Select Operation)
        - selects tuples that satisfy a given predicate.
        - use lowercase Greek letter sigma (σ)
            ex) σ dept_name =“Physics” (instructor)
                + select dept_name which equals "Physics"

    (2.6.2 The Project Operation)
        - unary operation that returns its argument relation, with certain attributes left out.
            -> any duplicate rows are eliminated.
        - use uppercase Greek letter pi (Π)
            ex) Π ID, name, salary (instructor)
                + select (DISTINCT) ID, name, salary from instructor

    (2.6.3 Composition of Relational Operations)
        - relational-algebra operations can be composed together into a "relational-algebra expression".
            ex) Π name (σ dept_name =“Physics” (instructor))
                + select name from instructor where dept_name equals "Physics"

    (2.6.4 The Cartesian-Product Operation)
        - denoted by a cross (x), allows us to combine information from any two relations.
            ex) r1 x r2 (Cartesian product of relations r1 and r2)

    (2.6.5 The Join Operation)
        - combine a selection and a Cartesian product into a single operation.
            ex) r ⋈θ s = σθ(r × s)

    (2.6.6 Set Operations)
        - "union": ∪
            1) must ensure that the input relations to the union operation have the same number of attributes;
                -> the number of attributes of a relation is referred to as its "arity".

            2) when the attirubtes have associated types, the types of the ith attributes of both input relations must be the same, for each i.

        - "intersection": ∩
            -> allows us to find tuples that are in both the input relations.

        - "set-difference" operation: -
            ex) r - s (relation containing those tuples in r but not in s)

    (2.6.7 The Assignment Operation)
        - denoted by ← (works like assignment in a programming language)
            ex) courses_fall_2017 ← Π course_id (σ semester =“Fall” ∧ year=2017 (section))
                (assigning the result of right operation into left variable)

    (2.6.8 The Rename Operation)
        - results of the relational-algebra expressions do not have a name that we can use to refer to them.
            -> useful in some cases to give them names; the "rename" operator.

        - denoted by the lowercase Greek letter rho (ρ)
            ex) ρx (E) : result of expression E under the name x

    (2.6.9 Equivalent Queries)
        - query with two different operations may be equivalent (same results)
            -> but have different performances.
            -> Query optimizers in db systems find an efficient way of cmoputing the result, rather than following the exact sequence of steps specified in the query.
